 distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Lambeck","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places so named in Westphalia and Hesse.","Dutch: habitational name from any of the places called Lembeke in East and West Flanders, and in Tielt, Ooigem, Sint-Baafs-Vijve, and Wielsbeke, or from Lembeek in Brabant. Alternatively, of German origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Puttin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): variant of   Patten  . This surname is rare in Britain.","French (mainly Nord): variant of   Patin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Patten","meanings":["English:","occasionally a metonymic occupational name for a maker or seller of clogs, from Middle English <i>paten</i> ‘clog’ (Old French <i>patin</i>).","variant of   Patton   (a Middle English pet form of <i>Patrick</i>) with <i>-in</i> substituted for <i>-on</i>."]}]},{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilda Von Lambeck Puttin Heiress was born